The Control Unit (CU) is a crucial part of the CPU responsible for coordinating and controlling the execution of instructions.
It interprets program instructions, decodes them, and generates the necessary control signals to manage the operations of other CPU components.
Fetch: The Control Unit retrieves the next instruction from memory based on the address stored in the Program Counter.
Decode: The opcode of the instruction is decoded to determine the type of operation to be performed.
Execute: The actual operation specified by the instruction is carried out by the Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU) or other functional units.
Store: The results of the operation may be stored in memory or in a register, depending on the instruction.
Internally, the Control Unit operates using microinstructions, which are lower-level instructions that control the internal operations of the CPU.
